ARTICLE.TITLE: 12 new COVID cases in NSW
ARTICLE.TEXT:
Another 12 cases of coronavirus were diagnosed across the state up to 8pm on Wednesday, with three of those having no known source.

Five cases were returned travellers in hotel quarantine, and four were locally acquired with a known source of infection.

One case linked to the Our Lady of Mercy College in Parramatta attended Westfield Liverpool on Friday August 7 from 10:30-11am and 12:30-1pm, and 5th Avenue Beauty Bar in Wetherill Park on August 8 from 2-3pm.

Anyone who was at these venues at those times is considered a casual contact and advised to watch for symptoms and get tested if any arise.

New South Wales also recorded its 53rd death from coronavirus, a woman in her 80s whose infection was linked to the Our Lady of Lebanon cluster.

She is believed to have been in the intensive care unit of a Sydney hospital before she died.

This is the first death in nearly two weeks, with the last on August 1, and announced on August 2.

Case numbers have continued to grow in the past few weeks, with 18 new cases announced on Tuesday, and a total of 135 active cases in the state.

Six patients are in ICU and being ventilated.

There have been 380 cases of coronavirus throughout New South Wales with no identified source.

The national death toll for coronavirus stands at 361.

12 new cases of #COVID19 have been diagnosed in NSW between 8pm on 11 August and 8pm on 12 August.



For the latest list of COVID-19 locations, visit: https://t.co/pqkRdfyEBr pic.twitter.com/3EdVLpBmq2 — NSW Health (@NSWHealth) August 13, 2020

Originally published as 12 new COVID cases in NSW
